  "32": {
    "John Trapp": "Upon man\u2019s flesh.] A Latine Postiller hence infers, in a hyperbolical sense, that priests are angels, not having human flesh.\nVer.\n32. Blot me, I pray thee.] God never revealed his love to Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` more than when he thus earnestly prayed for God\u2019s people. Joab never pleased David `[char_David_Rut_4]` better than when he made intercession for Absalom.\nVer.\n32. And he gave them in commandment.] Rabbi Menahem telleth us, that the former ancients of Israel, at the reading of the book of the law, covered their faces and said, \"He that heareth from the mouth of the reader is as he that heareth from the mouth of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`.\" The Jews at this day, in their synagogues, put on each man his Taleth or square vestment, turning it back about their necks, that so they may hear and pray with more attention and reverence. {a} {a} Leo. Modena.\nVer.\n32. And to devise curious works.] \"This also cometh forth from the Lord of hosts, who is wonderful in counsel, and excellent [v_Isa_28_29] in working.\" {#Isa 28:29} Pliny {a} makes mention of some famous painters, whose rare pieces were Oppidorum opibus venditae: sold for so many towns\u2019 wealth. A certain craftsman set a watch clock upon a ring that Charles V wore upon his finger. {b} King Ferdinand sent to Solyman the Turk, for a present, a wonderful globe of silver of most rare and curious device; daily expressing the hourly passing of the time, the motions of the planets, the change and full of the moon; lively expressing the wonderful conversions of the celestial frame. {c} To which I may well add that admirable invention of printing, a special blessing of God to mankind. {a} Lib. xxiii. {b} Sphinx Philos., p, 90. {c} Turk. Hist., fol.\n32. Which dwell therein. ] After that you shall be driven out of it.\nVer.\n32. Which dwell therein.] After that you shall be driven out of it. [v_Psa_44_11]\nVer.\n32. Passeth under the rod.] Coloured at the end with red, to [v_Jer_33_13] mark out the tenth, as they passed out. See #Jer 33:",
    "Lloyd R. Bailey": "Brief material on \u201cResheph\u201d and \u201cDeber\u201d may be\nfound in T. H. Gaster, \u201cDemon, Demonology,\u201d in vol. 1 of IDB, ed. George Arthur Buttrick (Nashville:\nAbingdon Press, 1962), 817-"
  },
  "5": {
    "John Trapp": "And in cutting of stones.] Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` might well doubt where he should find fit workmen among those brick makers for Egypt.\nVer.\n5. A feast to Jehovah.] Whom these idolators pretended to worship in the golden calf; as did also Jehu, {#2Ki 10:16,29 2Ch 11:15} and as the Papists at this day. But with what face can some of their Rabbis excuse this people from idolatry? or the Jesuits their image worshippers?\nVer.\n5. And consume thee.] God\u2019s threatenings are cordial, but [v_Isa_27_4] conditional. Minatur Deus ut non puniat. \"Fury is not in me.\" {#Isa 27:4} He punisheth not \"till there be no other remedy,\" {#2Ch 36:16} as the bee stings not till provoked.\nVer.\n5. And proclaimed the name of the Lord.] In answer to [v_Exo_33_18] Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`\u2019s prayer. {#Ex 33:18,19}\nVer.\nVer. 4-7, &c. Much of this chapter is to be read in the twenty-fifth, and elsewhere. See the notes there. [v_Exo_35_4]\nVer. 5. {See Trapp on \"Ex 35:4\"} [v_Exo_35_4]\n5. Dwell in your land safely. ] Confidently, fiducially, as boldly relying upon God\u2019s protection.\nVer.\n5. Dwell in your land safely.] Confidently, fiducially, as boldly relying upon God\u2019s protection.\nVer.\n5. From five years old.] Childhood and youth is vanity. There [v_Pro_22_15] is a bundle of folly in a child\u2019s heart. {#Pr 22:15} The same Greek word \u03bd\u03b7\u03c0\u03b9\u03bf\u03c2, signifieth a fool, and a child. And the Hebrew word [v_Ecc_11_10] used to signify youth, {#Ec 11:10} signifieth blackness or darkness, to note, that youth is a dark and dangerous age. Few Macariuses to be found, who, for his gravity in youth, was surnamed \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03b3\u03b5\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd, the old young man. {a} {a} Niceph.\nVer.\n5. Ver.",
    "Margaret S. Odell": "471"
  },
